A cardiac computed tomography was obtained following the catheterization, which delineated the relationship of the ventricular diverticula to the structures in the omphalocele (Figure 2
). At 17 months of age, the patient underwent elective surgical repair of the conduit and left pulmonary artery stenosis as well as resection of the diverticula. The operation was coordinated with pediatric general surgery for concurrent closure of the omphalocele. Following uneventful resternotomy, the heart was dissected with the exception of the diverticula, and aortobicaval cardiopulmonary bypass was initiated with cooling to 32°C. Once on bypass, the diverticula were dissected into the omphalocele through the diaphragmatic defect in the pericardium and completely delivered into the chest (Figure 3
). While true ectopia cordis was not present in this patient, the biventricular diverticula extended significantly beyond the chest wall into the omphalocele. At the base of the diverticula, a “septum” could be appreciated with continuation of the left anterior descending artery within the “interdiverticular groove.” After careful delineation of the coronary anatomy (no prior coronary angiography), a plane was developed in this septum so that vascular clamps could be placed across the left and right ventricular diverticula individually. The diverticula were each amputated beyond the clamps and the stumps oversewn with running 5-0 Prolene and reinforced with pledgeted sutures. The cut distal end of the left anterior descending artery was oversewn separately. Following resection of the diverticula, two small residual ASDs were closed via suture technique, and the stenosed homograft was excised. The proximal left pulmonary artery was enlarged with a pericardial patch and 14 mm Carpentier-Edwards porcine Dacron conduit implanted from the right ventricle to the confluence of the branch pulmonary arteries. The patient was subsequently weaned and separated from bypass with good biventricular function and stable hemodynamics. The patient’s condition allowed for immediate repair of the midline defect in the diaphragm and reduction and closure of the omphalocele by the pediatric general surgery team.
